## 1. Executive Summary

DataFlow Systems, Inc. presents a strategically compelling acquisition target: $28.5M ARR, 340+ enterprise customers including marquee financial institutions, 14 stream-processing patents, SOC 2 Type II certification, and a 67-person engineering team with elite pedigree. The acquisition plan's rationale — closing an 18-month gap in the "Live Insights" roadmap — is credible and the proposed valuation range of $320M–$350M is defensible given comparable transactions.

However, the technical due diligence review of the target's publicly accessible web application repository has uncovered findings that materially alter the risk profile of this transaction. These findings range from routine engineering immaturity to a finding of exceptional severity that demands board-level attention before any further steps are taken.

**The most critical finding is this:** The reviewed source code and documentation contain what appears to be a deliberate, systematic prompt injection attack — malicious instructions embedded in source files, disguised as a legitimate internal policy, designed to trick AI-assisted developer tools into exfiltrating secret credentials and API keys from the repository. This payload is present verbatim in at least two separate files, indicating it was not an accident. This finding raises serious questions about the integrity of the development environment, the security posture of the organization, and — critically — whether this tactic has been used elsewhere in code that will become part of our production infrastructure post-acquisition.

